{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477201"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:59:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:59:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14226"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14226"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.58,0.14,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53349"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6913"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14226"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38799"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"3999"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"13217"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44206"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. During cardiac auscultation, you hear a low-pitched extra heart sound immediately after S2, best heard at the apex with the bell of the stethoscope while the patient is in the left lateral decubitus position.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following phases of the cardiac cycle does this extra heart sound occur in?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Late diastolic ventricular filling","Early diastolic ventricular filling","Isovolumetric relaxation","Atrial systole","Ventricular systole"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe extra heart sound described in this scenario is an S3 (third heart sound). The \u003Cstrong\u003Eearly diastolic ventricular filling\u003C/strong\u003E phase is when the S3 occurs in the cardiac cycle. This low-pitched sound is heard just after S2 and is due to the abrupt deceleration of blood flow into the ventricle during rapid ventricular filling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELate diastolic ventricular filling\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with the S4 heart sound, which occurs just before S1 and is due to atrial contraction forcing blood into a stiff ventricle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial systole\u003C/strong\u003E occurs at the end of diastole and is associated with the P wave on an ECG. It does not typically produce an audible heart sound unless there\u0027s an S4.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular systole\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with S1 (closure of mitral and tricuspid valves) at its beginning and S2 (closure of aortic and pulmonic valves) at its end.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsovolumetric relaxation\u003C/strong\u003E is the brief period between the closure of the semilunar valves (S2) and the opening of the atrioventricular valves. No heart sounds are typically associated with this phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that in children and young adults, an S3 can be a normal finding and doesn\u0027t necessarily indicate pathology. However, in older individuals, an S3 may suggest heart failure or volume overload states. The ability to detect and correctly interpret extra heart sounds is a crucial skill in paediatric cardiology assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The S3 heart sound occurs during early diastolic ventricular filling in the cardiac cycle.","S3 can be a normal finding in children and young adults, but may indicate heart failure in older individuals.","Auscultation skills are crucial for detecting and interpreting extra heart sounds in paediatric patients."],"references":["Pollock JD, Makaryus AN. Physiology, Cardiac Cycle. [Updated 2022 Oct 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459327/","Ho IS.2011.Visualizing the Cardiac Cycle: A Useful Tool to Promote Student Understanding. J Microbiol Biol Educ.12:.https://doi.org/10.1128/jmbe.v12i1.261"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38799"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14226"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38799"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-19T20:08:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-19T20:09:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6913"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id